####################################### ### Generated from PreTeXt source ### on 2018-07-27T14:33:57-06:00 ### ### http://mathbook.pugetsound.edu ### ####################################### ## DBsubject() ## DBchapter() ## DBsection() ## Level() ## KEYWORDS() ## TitleText1(Discrete Mathematics) ## EditionText1() ## AuthorText1(Oscar Levin) ## Section1(not reported) ## Problem1(1.2.10) ## Author() ## Institution() ## Language(en-US)
DOCUMENT();
############################################################ # Load Macros ############################################################ loadMacros( "PGstandard.pl", "MathObjects.pl", "PGML.pl", "niceTables.pl", "AnswerFormatHelp.pl", "parserPopUp.pl", "PGcourse.pl", );
############################################################ # Header ############################################################ COMMENT('Authored in PreTeXt'); TEXT(beginproblem());
############################################################ # PG Setup ############################################################ Context('Numeric'); $true = PopUp( ["?","True","False","Not enough information"], "True", ); $false = PopUp( ["?","True","False","Not enough information"], "False", ); $na = PopUp( ["?","True","False","Not enough information"], "Not enough information", );
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Suppose [`P(x,y)`] is some binary predicate defined on a very small domain of discourse: just the integers 1, 2, 3, and 4. For each of the 16 pairs of these numbers, [`P(x,y)`] is either true or false, according to the following table ([`x`] values are rows, [`y`] values are columns).
>> [@DataTable( [ [[PGML(''), halign => 'r|', midrule => '1', rowcss => 'border-bottom: 1px solid; ', cellcss => 'border-right: 1px solid; ',], [PGML('1'),], [PGML('2'),], [PGML('3'),], [PGML('4'),], ], [[PGML('1'), halign => 'r|', cellcss => 'border-right: 1px solid; ',], PGML('T'), PGML('F'), PGML('F'), PGML('F'), ], [[PGML('2'), halign => 'r|', cellcss => 'border-right: 1px solid; ',], PGML('F'), PGML('T'), PGML('T'), PGML('F'), ], [[PGML('3'), halign => 'r|', cellcss => 'border-right: 1px solid; ',], PGML('T'), PGML('T'), PGML('T'), PGML('T'), ], [[PGML('4'), halign => 'r|', cellcss => 'border-right: 1px solid; ',], PGML('F'), PGML('F'), PGML('F'), PGML('F'), ], ], align => 'lllll', center => 0, );@]* <<
For example, [`P(1,3)`] is false, as indicated by the F in the first row, third column. Use the table to decide whether the following statements are true or false. a. [`\forall x \exists y P(x,y)\text{.}`] [_____]{$false}
a. [`\forall y \exists x P(x,y)\text{.}`] [_____]{$true}
a. [`\exists x \forall y P(x,y)\text{.}`] [_____]{$true}
a. [`\exists y \forall x P(x,y)\text{.}`] [_____]{$false}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION a. [`\forall x \exists y P(x,y)`] is false because when [`x = 4\text{,}`] there is no [`y`] which makes [`P(4,y)`] true.
a. [`\forall y \exists x P(x,y)`] is true. No matter what [`y`] is (i.e., no matter what column we are in) there is some [`x`] for which [`P(x,y)`] is true. In fact, we can always take [`x`] to be [`3\text{.}`]
a. [`\exists x \forall y P(x,y)`] is true. In particular [`x=3`] is such a number, so that no matter what [`y`] is, [`P(x,y)`] is true.
a. [`\exists y \forall x P(x,y)`] is false. In fact, no matter what [`y`] (column) we look at, there is always some [`x`] (row) which makes [`P(x,y)`] false.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
############################################################ # End Problem ############################################################
ENDDOCUMENT();

