############################################################ # PG Setup ############################################################ Context('Numeric'); $injective = PopUp( ["?", "Injective", "Surjective", "Bijective", "Neither"], "Injective", ); $surjective = PopUp( ["?", "Injective", "Surjective", "Bijective", "Neither"], "Surjective", ); $bijective = PopUp( ["?", "Injective", "Surjective", "Bijective", "Neither"], "Bijective", ); $neither = PopUp( ["?", "Injective", "Surjective", "Bijective", "Neither"], "Neither", );
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML The following functions all have [`\{1,2,3,4,5\}`] as both their domain and codomain. For each, determine whether it is (only) injective, (only) surjective, bijective, or neither injective nor surjective.
a. [`\newcommand{\twoline}[2]{\begin{pmatrix}#1 \\ #2 \end{pmatrix}}\newcommand{\amp}{&}f = \twoline{1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \amp 5}{3 \amp 3 \amp 3 \amp 3 \amp 3}\text{.}`] [_____]{$neither}
a. [`\newcommand{\twoline}[2]{\begin{pmatrix}#1 \\ #2 \end{pmatrix}}\newcommand{\amp}{&}f = \twoline{1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \amp 5}{2 \amp 3 \amp 1 \amp 5 \amp 4}\text{.}`] [_____]{$bijective}
a. [`f(x) = 6 - x\text{.}`] [_____]{$bijective}
a. [`\newcommand{\amp}{&}f(x) = \begin{cases} x/2 \amp \text{ if } x \text{ is even} \\ (x+1)/2 \amp \text{ if } x \text{ is odd}\end{cases}\text{.}`] [_____]{$neither}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION a. This is neither injective nor surjective. It is not injective because more than one element from the domain has 3 as its image. It is not surjective because there are elements of the codomain (1, 2, 4, and 5) that are not images of anything from the domain.
a. This is a bijection. Every element in the codomain is the image of _exactly_ one element of the domain.
a. This is a bijection. Note that we can write this function in two line notation as [`\newcommand{\twoline}[2]{\begin{pmatrix}#1 \\ #2 \end{pmatrix}}\newcommand{\amp}{&}f = \twoline{1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \amp 5}{5 \amp 4 \amp 3 \amp 2 \amp 1}\text{.}`]
a. In two line notation, this function is [`\newcommand{\twoline}[2]{\begin{pmatrix}#1 \\ #2 \end{pmatrix}}\newcommand{\amp}{&}f = \twoline{1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \amp 5}{1 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp 3}\text{.}`] From this we can quickly see it is neither injective (for example, 1 is the image of both 1 and 2) nor surjective (for example, 4 is not the image of anything).
END_PGML_SOLUTION
############################################################ # End Problem ############################################################
ENDDOCUMENT();

