statement.p:
Suppose f:\N \to \N satisfies the recurrence f(n+1) = f(n) + 3\text{.}  Note that this is not enough information to define the function, since we dont have an initial condition. For each of the initial conditions below, find the value of f(5)\text{.} 




f(0) = 0\text{.}




f(0) = 1\text{.}




f(0) = 2\text{.}




f(0) = 100\text{.}

solution.p:
For each case, you must use the recurrence to find f(1)\text{,} f(2) ... f(5)\text{.}  But notice each time you just add three to the previous.  We do this 5 times. 




f(5) = 15\text{.}




f(5) = 16\text{.}




f(5) = 17\text{.}




f(5) = 115\text{.}

