############################################################ # Load Macros ############################################################ loadMacros( "PGstandard.pl", "MathObjects.pl", "PGML.pl", "AnswerFormatHelp.pl", "PCCmacros.pl", "parserPopUp.pl", "parserRadioButtons.pl", "PGcourse.pl", );
############################################################ # Header ############################################################ COMMENT('Authored in PreTeXt'); TEXT(beginproblem());
############################################################ # PG Setup ############################################################ Context('Numeric'); $true = PopUp( ["?","True","False","Neither (not a statement)"], "True", ); $exists = RadioButtons( ["\(\exists x P(x)\) must be true.","\(\exists x P(x)\) must be false.","\(\exists x P(x)\) could be true or could be false."], "\(\exists x P(x)\) must be true.", # correct answer ); $forall = RadioButtons( ["\(\forall x P(x)\) must be true.","\(\forall x P(x)\) must be false.","\(\forall x P(x)\) could be true or could be false."], "\(\forall x P(x)\) could be true or could be false." # correct answer );
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Let [`P(x)`] be the predicate, "[`3x+1`] is even." a. Is [`P(5)`] true or false? [_____]{$true}
a. What, if anything, can you conclude about [`\exists x P(x)`] from the truth value of [`P(5)\text{?}`]
[@KeyboardInstructions(q?[_____]{$exists}?)@]**
a. What, if anything, can you conclude about [`\forall x P(x)`] from the truth value of [`P(5)\text{?}`]
[@KeyboardInstructions(q?[_____]{$forall}?)@]**
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION [`P(5)`] is the statement "[`3\cdot 5 + 1`] is even", which is true. Thus the statement [`\exists x P(x)`] is true (for example, 5 is such an [`x`]). However, we cannot tell anything about [`\forall x P(x)`] since we do not know the truth value of [`P(x)`] for _all_ elements of the domain of discourse. In this case, [`\forall x P(x)`] happens to be false (since [`P(4)`] is false, for example).
END_PGML_SOLUTION
############################################################ # End Problem ############################################################
ENDDOCUMENT();

####################################### ### Generated from PreTeXt source ### on 2018-07-27T14:33:58-06:00 ### ### http://mathbook.pugetsound.edu ### ####################################### ## DBsubject() ## DBchapter() ## DBsection() ## Level() ## KEYWORDS() ## TitleText1(Discrete Mathematics) ## EditionText1() ## AuthorText1(Oscar Levin) ## Section1(not reported) ## Problem1(2.5.10) ## Author() ## Institution() ## Language(en-US)
DOCUMENT();
############################################################ # Load Macros ############################################################ loadMacros( "PGstandard.pl", "MathObjects.pl", "PGML.pl", "AnswerFormatHelp.pl", "contextIntegerFunctions.pl", "PGcourse.pl", );
############################################################ # Header ############################################################ COMMENT('Authored in PreTeXt'); TEXT(beginproblem());
############################################################ # PG Setup ############################################################ Context("IntegerFunctions"); $ans1 = Compute("C(10,5)"); $ans2 = Compute("C(14,5)");
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Consider functions [`f:\{1,2,3,4,5\} \to \{0,1,2,\ldots,9\}\text{.}`] a. How many of these functions are strictly increasing? Explain. (A function is strictly increasing provided if [`\renewcommand{\v}{\vtx{above}{}}\newcommand{\lt}{<}a \lt b\text{,}`] then [`\renewcommand{\v}{\vtx{above}{}}\newcommand{\lt}{<}f(a) \lt f(b)\text{.}`])
[_____]{$ans1}
a. How many of the functions are non-decreasing? Explain. (A function is non-decreasing provided if [`\renewcommand{\v}{\vtx{above}{}}\newcommand{\lt}{<}a \lt b\text{,}`] then [`f(a) \le f(b)\text{.}`])
[_____]{$ans2}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION a. [`{10 \choose 5}\text{.}`] Note that a strictly increasing function is automatically injective. So the five outputs must all be different. So let's first pick which five outputs we will use: there are [`{10 \choose 5}`] ways to do this. Now how many ways are there to assign those outputs to the inputs [`1`] through 5? Only one way, since there is only one way to arrange numbers in increasing order.
a. [`{14 \choose 5}\text{.}`] This is in fact a stars and bars problem. The stars are the 5 inputs and the bars are the 9 spots between the 10 possible outputs. Think of it this way - we will specify [`f(1)\text{,}`] then [`f(2)\text{,}`] then [`f(3)\text{,}`] and so on in that order. Start with the possible output 0. We can use it as the output of [`f(1)\text{,}`] or we can switch to 1 as a potential output. Say we put [`f(1) = 1\text{.}`] Now we are at 1 (can't go back to 0). Should [`f(2) = 1\text{?}`] If yes, then we are putting down another star. If no, put down a bar and switch to 2. Maybe you switch to 3, then assign [`f(2) = 3`] and [`f(3) = 3`] (two more stars) before switching to 4 as a possible output. And so on.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
############################################################ # End Problem ############################################################
ENDDOCUMENT();

