############################################################ # Header ############################################################ COMMENT('Authored in PreTeXt'); TEXT(beginproblem());
############################################################ # PG Setup ############################################################ Context("IntegerFunctions"); $ans = Compute("C(13,7)");
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Suppose you planned on giving 7 gold stars to some of the 13 star students in your class. Each student can receive at most one star. How many ways can you do this?
[_____]{$ans}
Use PIE. Then, find the numeric answer in Pascal's triangle and explain why that makes sense.
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION Without any restriction, there would be [`{19\choose 7}`] ways to distribute the stars. Now we must use PIE to eliminate all distributions in which one or more student gets more than one star:
[``` {19 \choose 7} - \left[{13 \choose 1}{17 \choose 5} - {13\choose 2}{15 \choose 3} + {13\choose 3}{13 \choose 1}\right] = 1716. ```]
Interestingly enough, this number is also the value of [`{13 \choose 7}\text{,}`] which makes sense: if each student can have at most one star, we must just pick the 7 out of 13 students to receive them.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
############################################################ # End Problem ############################################################
ENDDOCUMENT();

